<br>
&quot;Aunt Maritzia, come away from here.  This isn't good for you.&quot;<br>
<br>
The voice brought her out of her reverie of Hate.  She knew who it was, the only one who ever followed her here.  Even her husband did not interfere when the brooding came upon her.<br>
<br>
&quot;Go away, Babed.  I have to do this.&quot;  She didn't even bother to look up at the tears that filled the young gnome's eyes and see the pleading that showed so plainly in her face.  &quot;I *need* to do this.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Aunt Maritzia, I know how much you hate Lucan, and you have reason to, after what he did to you...&quot;<br>
<br>
The gnome was suddenly thrown backward by the backhand form her aunt which she didn't expect.  For a cleric, she was quite strong, and her head rand for a moment before she rose from the ground.<br>
<br>
&quot;Never...NEVER...speak of that to me again.  Do you understand me?  DO YOU UNDERSTAND?!!!&quot;<br>
<br>
Babed looked at her aunt, seeing the unreasoning fury flowing from her, and just nodded.  She knew broaching the topic to her would be dangerous.  She was just lucky Maritzia didn't have offensive spells memorized.  She was bad about that, forgetting to have them ready when she was alone.  It was one reason why Babed followed her, to make sure she was safe.<br>
<br>
Maritzia was already sitting again, knees hugged to her chest watching the guards as they moved back and forth with her feverish, rage-filled eyes.  Babed knew what would come next, so she quietly left and returned to the Harvesters Hall.  Maybe she could find Maritzia's stash of brandy before she got home.  She knew her aunt wouldn't take the drink from the main hall.  She didn't want everyone to know her weakness.  Lately, though, she'd gotten good at hiding her brandy, or maybe she just had enough presence of mind to bring it home with her after her forays into East Commons.<br>
